{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507511"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:53:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:53:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2633"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2633"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.68,0.11,0.07,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2633"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54414"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2633"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2633"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39923"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1564"},{"type":"tags","id":"4439"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5613"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2977"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2985"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16294"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54414"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old woman is resting in the obstetrics unit after a long and difficult vaginal delivery of a baby boy. She presented to the labour ward yesterday morning with abdominal cramping and rupture of membranes. She was judged as being in early labour. Due to significant pain and distress, an epidural catheter was inserted and labour subsequently progressed without any further difficulty. The epidural catheter has now been removed. Over the last few hours, she has developed an excruciating headache which feels different from her usual migraines. It is made worse by standing up and relieved by lying flat. It is localised to the back of her head and is associated with some neck stiffness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures has likely been punctured to produce these symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Interspinous ligament","Dura mater","Ligamentum flavum","Epidural artery","Pia mater"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer to this question is \u003Cstrong\u003Edura mater\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a severe headache after insertion of an epidural catheter. The most likely cause is inadvertent puncture of the dura mater during the process of inserting the epidural needle and catheter. The intended target for an epidural catheter is the epidural space, a potential space that overlies the dura mater. If the dura mater is accidentally punctured during insertion of an epidural catheter, a post-dural headache can result. This can also sometimes occur following spinal anaesthesia (where the dura mater is intentionally pierced), however is much less common due to the smaller needles used.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EObstetric patients are at increased risk of post-dural puncture headache compared to non-obstetric patients receiving epidural analgesia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe underlying pathophysiology is thought to involve leakage of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) through the hole in the dura mater. If CSF leaks at a rate greater than that of fluid production, CSF pressure falls, particularly at the level of the brain when the patient is standing in the upright position. This also explains why the headache is improved when lying flat. The headache is generally localised to the frontal or occipital region and can be accompanied by other symptoms including neck stiffness, nausea, vertigo, photophobia and tinnitus. Treatment is generally supportive and most dural puncture headaches will have resolved after one week, although symptoms can occasionally linger for months. Severe headaches that interfere with a patient\u0027s activities can be treated with an epidural blood patch, a treatment that involves injection of the patient\u0027s own blood into the epidural space, effectively \u0022plugging\u0022 the dural puncture site.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring epidural catheterisation, the \u003Cstrong\u003Einterspinous ligament\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eligamentum flavum\u003C/strong\u003E are always traversed by the needle and catheter. The reason for this is that they lie along the path the needle must take in order to reach the epidural space. Piercing these structures is not associated with a headache.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eepidural arteries \u003C/strong\u003Eare another structure which can be inadvertently damaged during this procedure, however this would not cause the symptoms described. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epia mater\u003C/strong\u003E should never be pierced during epidural or spinal anaesthesia. Doing so would lead to immediate neurological symptoms and deficits, due to the intimate relationship this layer of the meninges has with the spinal cord, rather than a delayed headache.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Inadvertent puncture of the dura mater is an important cause of headache following epidural catheterisation."],"references":["Bezov D, Lipton RB, Ashina S. Post-dural puncture headache: part I diagnosis, epidemiology, etiology, and pathophysiology. Headache. Accepted for publication April 18, 2010. 2010 Apr;50(7):1144\u201352","Turnbull D., Shepherd D. Post-dural puncture headache: pathogenesis, prevention and treatment. British Journal of Anaesthesia\u202f: BJA. 2003 Nov;91(5):718\u201329"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39923"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2633"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39923"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-04T17:12:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-04T17:13:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2633"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54414"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"41","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/41"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc80","name":"Anatomy","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"t